Diagnosis:
The maculation pattern of this species is variable, but this species can be distinguished from other 

Anthidium

species by the following unique combination of characters: female, apical margin of clypeus coarsely serrate, nearly straight medially (
Fig. 23c
), T6 with shallow median emargination on distal margin (
Fig. 23h
); male, apical process of S8 rectangular, rounded apically (
Fig. 24h
), T7 lateral lobe rounded outwardly, coming to roughly right-angular tip, without adjacent flanges (
Fig. 24e
), S6 medially flat or rounded outward (
Fig. 24f
).

